{"title_page": "Alexander Aitken", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Alexander Aitkin}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Alexander C. Aitken\n| image             = File:Alexander Aitken.gif\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1895|04|01}}\n| birth_place       = [[Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1967|11|03|1895|04|01}}\n| death_place       = [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]\n| nationality       = [[New Zealand]]er\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]<br>[[Statistics]]\n| workplaces        = [[University of Edinburgh]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Edinburgh]]<br>[[University of Otago]]\n| thesis_title      = Smoothing of Data\n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = [[E. T. Whittaker]]<ref name=\"mathgene\">{{MathGenealogy|id=18577}}</ref>\n| known_for         = [[Aitken's array]]<br>[[Aitken's delta-squared process]]<br>[[Aitken interpolation]]\n| awards            = [[Fellow of the Royal Society]]<ref name=\"frs\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Whittaker | first1 = J. M. | last2 = Bartlett | first2 = M. S. | doi = 10.1098/rsbm.1968.0001 | title = Alexander Craig Aitken 1895-1967 | journal = [[Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society]] | volume = 14 | pages = 1 | year = 1968 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>\n| spouse            = [[Mary Winifred Betts Aitken]]\n}}\n\n'''Alexander Craig \"Alec\" Aitken''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|FRS|FRSE|FRSL}} {{postnominals|country=NZL|FRSNZ}} (1 April 1895 \u2013 3 November 1967) was one of [[New Zealand|New Zealand's]] most eminent mathematicians.<ref name=\"edge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nzedge.com/heroes/aitken.html|title=Alexander Aitken THE HUMAN COMPUTER|publisher=NZ Edge|access-date=7 December 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203193156/http://nzedge.com/heroes/aitken.html|archive-date=3 February 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"actuator\">{{MacTutor|id=Aitken|title=Alexander Aitken}}</ref> In a 1935 paper he introduced the concept of [[generalized least squares]], along with now standard [[Matrix (mathematics)|vector/matrix notation]] for the [[linear regression model]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Aitken | first1 = A. C. | year = 1935 | title = On Least Squares and Linear Combinations of Observations | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society of Edinburgh | volume = 55 | issue = | pages = 42\u201348 }}</ref> Another influential paper co-authored with his student [[Harold Silverstone]] established the lower bound on the variance of an [[estimator]],<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Aitken | first1 = A. C. | last2 = Silverstone | first2 = H. | year = 1942 | title = On the Estimation of Statistical Parameters | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society of Edinburgh | volume = 61 | issue = | pages = 186\u2013194 }}</ref> now known as [[Cram\u00e9r\u2013Rao bound]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=L. R. |last=Shenton |title=The so-called Cramer\u2013Rao inequality |journal=[[The American Statistician]] |year=1970 |volume=24 |issue=2 |page=36 |jstor=2681931 }}</ref> He was elected to the [[Royal Society of Literature]] for his [[World War I]] memoir, ''Gallipoli to the Somme''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/103175807/review-gallipoli-to-the-somme-recollections-of-a-new-zealand-infantryman-by-alexander-aitken|title=Review: Gallipoli to the Somme: Recollections of a New Zealand Infantryman by Alexander Aitken|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nAitken was born on 1 April 1895 in [[Dunedin]], the eldest of the seven children of  Elizabeth Towers and William Aitken. He was of Scottish descent, his grandfather having emigrated from the Borders in 1868. He was educated at [[Otago Boys' High School]] in Dunedin (1908\u201313) and won the Thomas Baker Calculus Scholarship in his last year at school. He saw active service during [[World War I]] with the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]], at [[Gallipoli Campaign|Gallipoli]], in Egypt, and at the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. He was wounded at the [[Battle of the Somme|Somme]].<ref>A. C. Aitken (1963). ''Gallipoli to the Somme: Recollections of a New Zealand infantryman''. Oxford.</ref>\n\nAitken graduated with an [[Master of Arts|MA]] degree from the [[University of Otago]] in 1920, then worked as a schoolmaster at Otago Boys' High School from 1920\u20133.\n\nAitken studied for a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degree at the [[University of Edinburgh]], in Scotland, where his dissertation, \"Smoothing of Data\", was considered so impressive that he was awarded a [[Doctor of Science|DSc]] degree in 1925.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aitken|first=A. C.|date=1925|title=Graduation of observational data|url=http://hdl.handle.net/1842/26479|journal=|language=en|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"edge\" /> Aitken's impact at the University had been so great that he had been elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]] (FRSE) the year before the award of his degree, upon the proposal of [[Sir Edmund Whittaker]], [[Sir Charles Galton Darwin]], [[Edward Copson]] and [[David Gibb (mathematician)|David Gibb]]. Aitken was awarded the Makdougall-Brisbane Prize for 1930\u201332, and was active in the affairs of the RSE, serving as Councillor (1934\u201336), Secretary to Ordinary Meetings (1936\u201340), and Vice-President (1948\u201351; 1956\u201359). He was also an active member of the [[Edinburgh Mathematical Society]] and a Fellow of the [[Faculty of Actuaries]].\n\nAitken spent his entire career at the University of Edinburgh, working as lecturer in Actuarial Mathematics & Statistics (1925\u201336), Reader in Statistics (1936\u201346), and finally Professor of Mathematics (1946\u201365).\n\nDuring World War II he worked in [[Hut 6]] [[Bletchley Park]] decrypting [[ENIGMA]] code.<ref name=\"odbn\">{{Cite journal| title = Aitken, Alexander Craig | journal = The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/30357 | year = 2004 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>\n\nAitken was one of the best [[mental calculator]]s known, and had a prodigious memory. He knew the first 1000 digits of <math>\\pi</math>, the 96 recurring digits of 1/97, and memorised the ''[[Aeneid]]'' in high school. However, his inability to forget the horrors he witnessed in [[World War I]] led to recurrent [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] throughout his life.<ref name=\"edge\" />\n\nAitken was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS) in 1936<ref name=\"frs\"/> and an [[Fellow of the Royal Society of New Zealand|Honorary Fellow of the Royal Society of New Zealand]] (Hon FRSNZ) in 1940,<ref>[http://www.royalsociety.org.nz/publications/reports/yearbooks/year2000/past-honorary-fellows/ Honorary Fellows, 1870-2000] - website of the Royal Society of New Zealand</ref> both for his work in statistics, [[algebra]] and [[numerical analysis]]. He was an accomplished writer, being elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature]] (FRSL) in 1964 in response to the publication of his war memoirs. He was also an excellent musician, being described by [[Eric Fenby]] as the most accomplished amateur musician he had ever known, and was a champion athlete in his younger days.\n\n==Awards and honours==\n\nThe [[New Zealand Mathematical Society]] and [[London Mathematical Society]] Aitken Lectureship occurs every two years (in odd-numbered years) when a mathematician from New Zealand is invited by both Societies to give lectures at different universities around the UK over a period of several weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nzmathsoc.org.nz/?activities |website=New Zealand Mathematical Society |accessdate=20 July 2018|title=Activities of the Society }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lms.ac.uk/events/lectures/forder-and-aitken-lectureship |website=London Mathematical Society |title=LMS-NZMS Forder and Aitken Lectureships|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn annual \"Aitken Prize\" is awarded by the [[New Zealand Mathematical Society]] for the best student talk at their colloquium. The prize was inaugurated in 1995 at the [[University of Otago]]'s Aitken Centenary Conference, a joint mathematics and statistics conference held to remember Aitken 100 years after his birth.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married [[Mary Winifred Betts Aitken|Mary Winifred Betts]], a lecturer in biology and the first female lecturer appointed to the University of Otago, in 1920. They had a daughter and a son. Aitken died on 3 November 1967, in [[Edinburgh]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*I. M. L. Hunter, An exceptional talent for calculative thinking, ''British Journal of Psychology'' 53 (3) (1962), 243\u2013258.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040601164403/http://ifs.massey.ac.nz/mathnews/centrefolds/63/Apr1995.shtml New Zealand Mathematical Society Newsletter, Number 63, April 1995 (Centerfold)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090203193156/http://nzedge.com/heroes/aitken.html NZ Heroes page on Aitken]\n*[http://www.austms.org.au/Publ/Gazette/1995/Mar95/aitken.html  A.C. Aitken (1895\u20131967)], P.C. Fenton, Gazette of the Australian Mathematical Society, March 1995\n*[http://davegiles.blogspot.com/2011/07/alexander-aitken.html Alexander Aitken, Econometrics Beat: Dave Giles' Blog]\n*[http://www.aam314.vzz.net/Aitken.html ''Times'' obituary]\n*[http://www.royalsoc.ac.uk/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqSearch=RefNo=='EC/1936/01'&dsqDb=Catalog Royal Society citation]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060515020350/http://www.math.waikato.ac.nz/NZMS/aitken05.html Aitken prize]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070216003420/http://www.mentalcalculation.com/misc/bbc1954.html Transcript of 1954 radio interview with Aitken and another mental calculator]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Es7wHodd9M Video footage of Aitken decimalising 19/23]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aitken, Alexander Craig}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dunedin]]\n[[Category:People educated at Otago Boys' High School]]\n[[Category:University of Otago alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Mental calculators]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of English descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:New Zealand mathematicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand mathematicians]]\n[[Category:New Zealand memoirists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male writers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:New Zealand statisticians]]\n[[Category:Scottish memoirists]]\n[[Category:Scottish statisticians]]\n[[Category:Bletchley Park people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish mathematicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Alexander Aitkin}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Alexander C. Aitken\n| image             = File:Alexander Aitken.gif\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1895|04|01}}\n| birth_place       = [[Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1967|11|03|1895|04|01}}\n| death_place       = [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]\n| nationality       = [[New Zealand]]er\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]<br>[[Statistics]]\n| workplaces        = [[University of Edinburgh]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Edinburgh]]<br>[[University of Otago]]\n| thesis_title      = Smoothing of Data\n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = [[E. T. Whittaker]]<ref name=\"mathgene\">{{MathGenealogy|id=18577}}</ref>\n| known_for         = [[Aitken's array]]<br>[[Aitken's delta-squared process]]<br>[[Aitken interpolation]]\n| awards            = [[Fellow of the Royal Society]]<ref name=\"frs\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Whittaker | first1 = J. M. | last2 = Bartlett | first2 = M. S. | doi = 10.1098/rsbm.1968.0001 | title = Alexander Craig Aitken 1895-1967 | journal = [[Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society]] | volume = 14 | pages = 1 | year = 1968 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>\n| spouse            = [[Mary Winifred Betts Aitken]]\n}}\n\n'''Alexander Craig \"Alec\" Aitken''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|FRS|FRSE|FRSL}} {{postnominals|country=NZL|FRSNZ}} (1 April 1895 \u2013 3 November 1967) was one of [[New Zealand|New Zealand's]] most eminent mathematicians.<ref name=\"edge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nzedge.com/heroes/aitken.html|title=Alexander Aitken THE HUMAN COMPUTER|publisher=NZ Edge|access-date=7 December 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203193156/http://nzedge.com/heroes/aitken.html|archive-date=3 February 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"actuator\">{{MacTutor|id=Aitken|title=Alexander Aitken}}</ref> In a 1935 paper he introduced the concept of [[generalized least squares]], along with now standard [[Matrix (mathematics)|vector/matrix notation]] for the [[linear regression model]].<ref>A. C. Aitken (1935). \"On Least Squares and Linear Combinations of Observations\", ''Proceedings of the Royal Society of Edinburgh'', 55, 42\u201348.</ref> Another influential paper co-authored with his student [[Harold Silverstone]] established the lower bound on the variance of an [[estimator]],<ref>A. C. Aitken and H. Silverstone (1942). \"On the Estimation of Statistical Parameters\", ''Proceedings of the Royal Society of Edinburgh'', 1942, 61, 186\u2013194.</ref> now known as [[Cram\u00e9r\u2013Rao bound]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=L. R. |last=Shenton |title=The so-called Cramer\u2013Rao inequality |journal=[[The American Statistician]] |year=1970 |volume=24 |issue=2 |page=36 |jstor=2681931 }}</ref> He was elected to the [[Royal Society of Literature]] for his [[World War I]] memoir, ''Gallipoli to the Somme''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/103175807/review-gallipoli-to-the-somme-recollections-of-a-new-zealand-infantryman-by-alexander-aitken|title=Review: Gallipoli to the Somme: Recollections of a New Zealand Infantryman by Alexander Aitken|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nAitken was born on 1 April 1895 in [[Dunedin]], the eldest of the seven children of  Elizabeth Towers and William Aitken. He was of Scottish descent, his grandfather having emigrated from the Borders in 1868. He was educated at [[Otago Boys' High School]] in Dunedin (1908\u201313) and won the Thomas Baker Calculus Scholarship in his last year at school. He saw active service during [[World War I]] with the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]], at [[Gallipoli Campaign|Gallipoli]], in Egypt, and at the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. He was wounded at the [[Battle of the Somme|Somme]].<ref>A. C. Aitken (1963). ''Gallipoli to the Somme: Recollections of a New Zealand infantryman''. Oxford.</ref>\n\nAitken graduated with an [[Master of Arts|MA]] degree from the [[University of Otago]] in 1920, then worked as a schoolmaster at Otago Boys' High School from 1920\u20133.\n\nAitken studied for a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degree at the [[University of Edinburgh]], in Scotland, where his dissertation, \"Smoothing of Data\", was considered so impressive that he was awarded a [[Doctor of Science|DSc]] degree in 1925.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aitken|first=A. C.|date=1925|title=Graduation of observational data|url=http://hdl.handle.net/1842/26479|journal=|language=en|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"edge\" /> Aitken's impact at the University had been so great that he had been elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]] (FRSE) the year before the award of his degree, upon the proposal of [[Sir Edmund Whittaker]], [[Sir Charles Galton Darwin]], [[Edward Copson]] and [[David Gibb (mathematician)|David Gibb]]. Aitken was awarded the Makdougall-Brisbane Prize for 1930\u201332, and was active in the affairs of the RSE, serving as Councillor (1934\u201336), Secretary to Ordinary Meetings (1936\u201340), and Vice-President (1948\u201351; 1956\u201359). He was also an active member of the [[Edinburgh Mathematical Society]] and a Fellow of the [[Faculty of Actuaries]].\n\nAitken spent his entire career at the University of Edinburgh, working as lecturer in Actuarial Mathematics & Statistics (1925\u201336), Reader in Statistics (1936\u201346), and finally Professor of Mathematics (1946\u201365).\n\nDuring World War II he worked in [[Hut 6]] [[Bletchley Park]] decrypting [[ENIGMA]] code.<ref name=\"odbn\">{{Cite journal| title = Aitken, Alexander Craig | journal = The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/30357 | year = 2004 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>\n\nAitken was one of the best [[mental calculator]]s known, and had a prodigious memory. He knew the first 1000 digits of <math>\\pi</math>, the 96 recurring digits of 1/97, and memorised the ''[[Aeneid]]'' in high school. However, his inability to forget the horrors he witnessed in [[World War I]] led to recurrent [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] throughout his life.<ref name=\"edge\" />\n\nAitken was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS) in 1936<ref name=\"frs\"/> and an [[Fellow of the Royal Society of New Zealand|Honorary Fellow of the Royal Society of New Zealand]] (Hon FRSNZ) in 1940,<ref>[http://www.royalsociety.org.nz/publications/reports/yearbooks/year2000/past-honorary-fellows/ Honorary Fellows, 1870-2000] - website of the Royal Society of New Zealand</ref> both for his work in statistics, [[algebra]] and [[numerical analysis]]. He was an accomplished writer, being elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature]] (FRSL) in 1964 in response to the publication of his war memoirs. He was also an excellent musician, being described by [[Eric Fenby]] as the most accomplished amateur musician he had ever known, and was a champion athlete in his younger days.\n\n==Awards and honours==\n\nThe [[New Zealand Mathematical Society]] and [[London Mathematical Society]] Aitken Lectureship occurs every two years (in odd-numbered years) when a mathematician from New Zealand is invited by both Societies to give lectures at different universities around the UK over a period of several weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nzmathsoc.org.nz/?activities |website=New Zealand Mathematical Society |accessdate=20 July 2018|title=Activities of the Society }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lms.ac.uk/events/lectures/forder-and-aitken-lectureship |website=London Mathematical Society |title=LMS-NZMS Forder and Aitken Lectureships|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn annual \"Aitken Prize\" is awarded by the [[New Zealand Mathematical Society]] for the best student talk at their colloquium. The prize was inaugurated in 1995 at the [[University of Otago]]'s Aitken Centenary Conference, a joint mathematics and statistics conference held to remember Aitken 100 years after his birth.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married [[Mary Winifred Betts Aitken|Mary Winifred Betts]], a lecturer in biology and the first female lecturer appointed to the University of Otago, in 1920. They had a daughter and a son. Aitken died on 3 November 1967, in [[Edinburgh]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*I. M. L. Hunter, An exceptional talent for calculative thinking, ''British Journal of Psychology'' 53 (3) (1962), 243\u2013258.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040601164403/http://ifs.massey.ac.nz/mathnews/centrefolds/63/Apr1995.shtml New Zealand Mathematical Society Newsletter, Number 63, April 1995 (Centerfold)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090203193156/http://nzedge.com/heroes/aitken.html NZ Heroes page on Aitken]\n*[http://www.austms.org.au/Publ/Gazette/1995/Mar95/aitken.html  A.C. Aitken (1895\u20131967)], P.C. Fenton, Gazette of the Australian Mathematical Society, March 1995\n*[http://davegiles.blogspot.com/2011/07/alexander-aitken.html Alexander Aitken, Econometrics Beat: Dave Giles' Blog]\n*[http://www.aam314.vzz.net/Aitken.html ''Times'' obituary]\n*[http://www.royalsoc.ac.uk/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqSearch=RefNo=='EC/1936/01'&dsqDb=Catalog Royal Society citation]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060515020350/http://www.math.waikato.ac.nz/NZMS/aitken05.html Aitken prize]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070216003420/http://www.mentalcalculation.com/misc/bbc1954.html Transcript of 1954 radio interview with Aitken and another mental calculator]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Es7wHodd9M Video footage of Aitken decimalising 19/23]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aitken, Alexander Craig}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dunedin]]\n[[Category:People educated at Otago Boys' High School]]\n[[Category:University of Otago alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Mental calculators]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of English descent