{"title_page": "Gaston Glass", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Gaston Glass\n| image        = Gaston Glass 1921.jpg\n| caption      = Glass in 1921\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1899|12|31}}\n| birth_place  = [[Paris]], France\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1965|11|11|1899|12|31}}\n| death_place  = [[Santa Monica, California]], US\n| years_active = 1917\u20131943\n| occupation   = Actor, producer\n}}\n[[File:Humoresque (1920) 1.jpg|thumb|[[Alma Rubens]] and Glass in ''[[Humoresque (1920 film)|Humoresque]]'' (1920).]]\n[[Image:There Are No Villains (1921) 1.jpg|right|thumb|250px|With [[Viola Dana]] in ''There Are No Villains'' (1921)]]\n[[Image:The Red Mark (1928) 1.jpg|right|thumb|250px|With [[Nina Quartero]], in ''The Red Mark'' (1928 promotional photo)]]\n\n'''Gaston Glass''' (December 31, 1899 &ndash; November 11, 1965) was a French-born American actor and producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=OJ5-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=%22Gaston+Glass%22+actor&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiCyszivaThAhU8TRUIHWaLDlkQ6AEINDAC#v=onepage&q=%22Gaston+Glass%22+actor&f=false|title=The Call of the Heart: John M. Stahl and Hollywood Melodrama|first1=Bruce|last1=Babington|first2=Charles|last2=Barr|date=November 7, 2018|publisher=Indiana University Press|accessdate=March 28, 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref> He was born '''Jacques Gaston Oscar Glass''' in [[Paris]] and died in [[Santa Monica, California]]. He was the father of the composer [[Paul Glass]] (born in 1934).\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* ''[[The Corsican Brothers (1917 film)|The Corsican Brothers]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[Let's Elope (film)|Let's Elope]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[Oh, You Women!]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[God's Crucible]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Humoresque (1920 film)|Humoresque]]'' (1920)\n* ''[[The World and His Wife]]'' (1920)\n* ''[[The Branded Woman]]'' (1920)\n* ''[[Her Winning Way]]'' (1921)\n* ''[[There 