{"title_page": "Cristina (singer)", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Cristina\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Cristina Monet-Palaci\n| alias               = Cristina Monet Zilkha\n| birth_place         = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1959|1|2}}\n| death_date          =  {{death date and age|2020|4|1|1959|1|2}}\n| origin              = [[New York City]], US\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = [[No wave]], [[synthpop]]\n| occupation          = Singer\n| years_active        = 1978\u20131984\n| label               = [[ZE Records]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Cristina Monet Zilkha''' ({{nee}} '''Monet-Palaci''',<ref name=engaged/> January 2, 1959 \u2013 April 1, 2020),<ref name=\"wheeler1\">{{cite news |last1=Wheeler |first1=Andr\u00e9 |title=Things Fall Apart singer Cristina reportedly dies from coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/01/pop-singer-cristina-coronavirus-us |accessdate=2 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> known during her recording career [[mononymously]] as '''Cristina''', was an American singer and writer, best known for her [[new wave]] recordings made for [[ZE Records]] in the late 1970s and early 1980s in [[New York City]].\n\n==Biography==\nA [[Harvard]] dropout,<ref name=\"rocks\">[http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/rocks_cristina.html Cristina * Boston Globe article (1980)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the daughter of a French psychoanalyst and an American illustrator-novelist-playwright, she was working as a writer for ''[[The Village Voice]]'' when she met [[Michael Zilkha]], who later became her husband.<ref name=\"queen\">[http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/queen_cristina.html Cristina * Time Out New York article (2004)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=engaged>{{cite web |title=Cristina Monet-Palaci And Michael Zilkha Engaged |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/12/style/cristina-monet-palaci-and-michael-zilkha-engaged.html |publisher= New York Times| accessdate=28 June 2018 |date=December 12, 1982}}</ref> A wealthy heir to England's Mothercare retail empire, Zilkha started ZE Records with [[Michel Esteban]]. Zilkha persuaded her to record a song titled \"Disco Clone\", an eccentric pastiche dance record written by Ronald Melrose, a classmate of hers at Harvard.<ref>[http://www.zerecords.com/2010/about_interview_1.php ''Strange Days'' magazine: 2009 interview with Michel Esteban] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916210655/http://www.zerecords.com/2010/about_interview_1.php |date=September 16, 2010 }}</ref> The original recording, released as ZE001 in 1978, was produced by [[John Cale]] and was the first to be issued on the ZE label.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://lineout.thestranger.com/2007/03/cristina_disco_clone_prod_by_john_cale |title=Cristina \u2013 Disco Clone Prod. By John Cale {{!}} Line Out {{!}} The Stranger's Music Blog {{!}} The Stranger {{!}} Seattle's Only Newspaper<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=July 28, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717033928/http://lineout.thestranger.com/2007/03/cristina_disco_clone_prod_by_john_cale |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A later version featured the uncredited [[Kevin Kline]] trying to seduce Cristina,<ref name=\"queen\" /> replacing [[Anthony Haden-Guest]] on the original record. <ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=POIVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT167&lpg=PT167&dq=%22Disco+Clone%22+Haden+Guest&source=bl&ots=LOzWqcJ1ph&sig=ACfU3U3p9xgB4JOfQg5L6IDz1oOc5BHsMw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiFhePams_mAhVjolwKHQVRCTIQ6AEwBXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Disco%20Clone%22%20Haden%20Guest&f=false Anthony Haden-Guest, ''The Last Party: Studio 54, Disco, and the Culture of the Night'', Open Road Media, 2015]</ref>\n\n\"Disco Clone\" was a cult success and encouraged ZE to release a full-length album in 1980, which was produced by [[August Darnell]] of [[Kid Creole & The Coconuts]].<ref name=\"queen\" /> The album was reissued as ''Doll in the Box''. Cristina also issued on a 12\" single a cover of [[Peggy Lee]]'s \"[[Is That All There Is?]]\" with new, satirical lyrics. Its authors [[Leiber and Stoller]] sued and successfully got it withdrawn for many years.<ref name=\"rocks\" /> Later, she released a cover of [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Drive My Car]]\" (also released as \"Baby You Can Drive My Car\"). She released the track \"Things Fall Apart\", produced by [[Was (Not Was)]], on ZE's ''[[A Christmas Record|Christmas Record]]'', in 1981.\n\nCristina's second album ''Sleep It Off'' was produced by [[Don Was]] and released in 1984 with a sleeve design by [[Jean-Paul Goude]] (a year before he used the same idea for [[Grace Jones]]). The lyrics satirized urban decadence with often dry, sarcastic delivery. The record flopped, and Cristina retired to domestic life in [[Texas]]. The album was re-released in 2004 with six bonus tracks, two of which were produced (and one co-written) by [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Cristina \u2014 Sleep It Off |url=https://www.discogs.com/Cristina-Sleep-It-Off/release/554612 |website=discogs.com |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nMonet-Palaci and Zilkha divorced in 1990, and she returned to New York City.<ref name=\"queen\" /> She later contributed learned essays and reviews to publications such as London's ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' while battling a debilitating illness.<ref name=\"queen\" /> Her two albums for ZE were reissued in 2004.<ref>[http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/1934 Dusted Reviews \u2013 Cristina<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nCristina died on April 1, 2020, at the age of 61, reportedly from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=wheeler1 />\n\n==Discography==\n{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist       = Cristina\n| Image        = \n| Caption      = \n| Studio       = 2\n| Live         = \n| Compilation  = \n| Video        = \n| Music videos = \n| Tribute      = \n| EP           = \n| Singles      = 6\n| Singles link = \n| B-sides      = \n| Soundtrack   = \n| References   = \n}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n* ''Cristina''  (1980, ZE Records)\n* ''[[Sleep It Off]]'' (1984, ZE Records)\n* ''Doll in the Box'' (2004, ZE Records) \u2013 Expanded re-issue of ''Cristina''\n* ''Sleep It Off'' (2004, ZE Records) \u2013 Expanded re-issue\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Disco Clone\" (1978)\n* \"[[Is That All There Is?]]\" (1980)\n* \"[[Drive My Car]]\" (also released as \"Baby You Can Drive My Car\") (1980)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Cristina-Drive-My-Car/master/196274 |title=Cristina \u2013 Drive My Car |author=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=2014-07-25}}</ref>\n* \"[[La Poup\u00e9e qui fait non]]\" (1980)\n* \"Things Fall Apart\" (1981)\n* \"Ticket to the Tropics\" (1984)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/ Fan site]\n* [http://zerecords.com/artist/12/cristina.html Discography on ZE Records]\n* [https://www.discogs.com/artist/55646-Cristina Cristina] at [[Discogs]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140202185748/http://www2.odn.ne.jp/airstructures/review%20newwave%20diva.html#cristina Vinyl discography] at the [[Wayback Machine]]\n* [http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/queen_cristina.html 2004 interview]\n* [http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/rocks_cristina.html 1980 review]\n* [http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/1934 Dusted review of album reissues]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/12/style/cristina-monet-palaci-and-michael-zilkha-engaged.html  1982 New York Times wedding notice]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110929034859/http://www.richardstrange.com/writing/writeb8.htm Essay] by [[Richard Strange]] at the Wayback Machine\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cristina}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:No wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:ZE Records artists]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Cristina\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Cristina Monet-Palaci\n| alias               = Cristina Monet Zilkha\n| birth_place         = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1959|1|2}}\n| death_date          =  {{death date and age|2020|4|1|1959|1|2}}\n| origin              = [[New York City]], US\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = [[No wave]], [[synthpop]]\n| occupation          = Singer\n| years_active        = 1978\u20131984\n| label               = [[ZE Records]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Cristina Monet Zilkha''' ({{nee}} '''Monet-Palaci''',<ref name=engaged/> January 2, 1959 \u2013 April 1, 2020),<ref name=\"wheeler1\">{{cite news |last1=Wheeler |first1=Andr\u00e9 |title=Things Fall Apart singer Cristina reportedly dies from coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/01/pop-singer-cristina-coronavirus-us |accessdate=2 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> known during her recording career [[mononymously]] as '''Cristina''', was an American singer and writer, best known for her [[new wave]] recordings made for [[ZE Records]] in the late 1970s and early 1980s in [[New York City]].\n\n==Biography==\nA [[Harvard]] dropout,<ref name=\"rocks\">[http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/rocks_cristina.html Cristina * Boston Globe article (1980)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the daughter of a French psychoanalyst and an American illustrator-novelist-playwright, she was working as a writer for ''[[The Village Voice]]'' when she met [[Michael Zilkha]], who later became her husband.<ref name=\"queen\">[http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/queen_cristina.html Cristina * Time Out New York article (2004)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=engaged>{{cite web |title=Cristina Monet-Palaci And Michael Zilkha Engaged |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/12/style/cristina-monet-palaci-and-michael-zilkha-engaged.html |publisher= New York Times| accessdate=28 June 2018 |date=December 12, 1982}}</ref> A wealthy heir to England's Mothercare retail empire, Zilkha started ZE Records with [[Michel Esteban]]. Zilkha persuaded her to record a song titled \"Disco Clone\", an eccentric pastiche dance record written by Ronald Melrose, a classmate of hers at Harvard.<ref>[http://www.zerecords.com/2010/about_interview_1.php ''Strange Days'' magazine: 2009 interview with Michel Esteban] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916210655/http://www.zerecords.com/2010/about_interview_1.php |date=September 16, 2010 }}</ref> The original recording, released as ZE001, was produced by [[John Cale]] and was the first to be issued on the ZE label.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://lineout.thestranger.com/2007/03/cristina_disco_clone_prod_by_john_cale |title=Cristina \u2013 Disco Clone Prod. By John Cale {{!}} Line Out {{!}} The Stranger's Music Blog {{!}} The Stranger {{!}} Seattle's Only Newspaper<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=July 28, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717033928/http://lineout.thestranger.com/2007/03/cristina_disco_clone_prod_by_john_cale |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A later version featured the uncredited [[Kevin Kline]] trying to seduce Cristina,<ref name=\"queen\" /> replacing [[Anthony Haden-Guest]] on the original record. <ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=POIVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT167&lpg=PT167&dq=%22Disco+Clone%22+Haden+Guest&source=bl&ots=LOzWqcJ1ph&sig=ACfU3U3p9xgB4JOfQg5L6IDz1oOc5BHsMw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiFhePams_mAhVjolwKHQVRCTIQ6AEwBXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Disco%20Clone%22%20Haden%20Guest&f=false Anthony Haden-Guest, ''The Last Party: Studio 54, Disco, and the Culture of the Night'', Open Road Media, 2015]</ref>\n\n\"Disco Clone\" was a cult success and encouraged ZE to release a full-length album in 1980, which was produced by [[August Darnell]] of [[Kid Creole & The Coconuts]].<ref name=\"queen\" /> The album was reissued as ''Doll in the Box''. Cristina also issued on a 12\" single a cover of [[Peggy Lee]]'s \"[[Is That All There Is?]]\" with new, satirical lyrics. Its authors [[Leiber and Stoller]] sued and successfully got it withdrawn for many years.<ref name=\"rocks\" /> Later, she released a cover of [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Drive My Car]]\" (also released as \"Baby You Can Drive My Car\"). She released the track \"Things Fall Apart\", produced by [[Was (Not Was)]], on ZE's ''[[A Christmas Record|Christmas Record]]'', in 1981.\n\nCristina's second album ''Sleep It Off'' was produced by [[Don Was]] and released in 1984 with a sleeve design by [[Jean-Paul Goude]] (a year before he used the same idea for [[Grace Jones]]). The lyrics satirized urban decadence with often dry, sarcastic delivery. The record flopped, and Cristina retired to domestic life in [[Texas]]. The album was re-released in 2004 with six bonus tracks, two of which were produced (and one co-written) by [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Cristina \u2014 Sleep It Off |url=https://www.discogs.com/Cristina-Sleep-It-Off/release/554612 |website=discogs.com |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nMonet-Palaci and Zilkha divorced in 1990, and she returned to New York City.<ref name=\"queen\" /> She later contributed learned essays and reviews to publications such as London's ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' while battling a debilitating illness.<ref name=\"queen\" /> Her two albums for ZE were reissued in 2004.<ref>[http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/1934 Dusted Reviews \u2013 Cristina<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nCristina died on April 1, 2020, at the age of 61, reportedly from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=wheeler1 />\n\n==Discography==\n{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist       = Cristina\n| Image        = \n| Caption      = \n| Studio       = 2\n| Live         = \n| Compilation  = \n| Video        = \n| Music videos = \n| Tribute      = \n| EP           = \n| Singles      = 6\n| Singles link = \n| B-sides      = \n| Soundtrack   = \n| References   = \n}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n* ''Cristina''  (1980, ZE Records)\n* ''[[Sleep It Off]]'' (1984, ZE Records)\n* ''Doll in the Box'' (2004, ZE Records) \u2013 Expanded re-issue of ''Cristina''\n* ''Sleep It Off'' (2004, ZE Records) \u2013 Expanded re-issue\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Disco Clone\" (1978)\n* \"[[Is That All There Is?]]\" (1980)\n* \"[[Drive My Car]]\" (also released as \"Baby You Can Drive My Car\") (1980)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Cristina-Drive-My-Car/master/196274 |title=Cristina \u2013 Drive My Car |author=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=2014-07-25}}</ref>\n* \"[[La Poup\u00e9e qui fait non]]\" (1980)\n* \"Things Fall Apart\" (1981)\n* \"Ticket to the Tropics\" (1984)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/ Fan site]\n* [http://zerecords.com/artist/12/cristina.html Discography on ZE Records]\n* [https://www.discogs.com/artist/55646-Cristina Cristina] at [[Discogs]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140202185748/http://www2.odn.ne.jp/airstructures/review%20newwave%20diva.html#cristina Vinyl discography] at the [[Wayback Machine]]\n* [http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/queen_cristina.html 2004 interview]\n* [http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/rocks_cristina.html 1980 review]\n* [http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/1934 Dusted review of album reissues]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/12/style/cristina-monet-palaci-and-michael-zilkha-engaged.html  1982 New York Times wedding notice]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110929034859/http://www.richardstrange.com/writing/writeb8.htm Essay] by [[Richard Strange]] at the Wayback Machine\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cristina}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:No wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:ZE Records artists]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ghmyrtle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cristina_(singer)"}
